The issue with your code is that you are using the `System.out.println(p.text());` statement to print the text of each paragraph to the console, but you are not redirecting the output to a file. To write the console output to a text file, you can use the `PrintWriter.write()` method to write the output to a file.

Here is the modified code that writes the console output to a text file:
```java
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.PrintWriter;
import java.io.File;
import java.io.*;

package htmlparser;

import org.jsoup.*;
import org.jsoup.nodes.*;
import org.jsoup.select.*;

public class Htmlparser {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String url = "http://cell-phone-providers-review.toptenreviews.com/cingular-review.html";
            Document doc = Jsoup.connect(url).get();
            Elements paragraphs = doc.select("p");
            PrintWriter out = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter("C:/Users/Desktop/outputtext.txt"));
            for (Element p : paragraphs) {
                out.write(p.text() + "\n");
            }
            out.close();
        } catch (IOException ex) {
            Logger.getLogger(Htmlparser.class.getName()).log(Level.SEVERE, null, ex);
        }
    }
}
```
In this code, we are using the `FileWriter` class to create a `PrintWriter` object that writes to a file. We then loop through each paragraph and use the `write()` method to write the text to the file, followed by a newline character (`\n`) to ensure that each paragraph is on a separate line. Finally, we close the `PrintWriter` object to ensure that the file is properly closed.

The output of this code will be a text file named `outputtext.txt` in the specified directory with one paragraph per line.
